So that sort of echoes what we expect to see.

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:30.239
And if you scroll a little bit to the right,

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:35.279
we see something called units, pass, and fail.

00:07:35.279 --> 00:07:37.519
OK, so units are, for each step,

00:07:37.519 --> 00:07:40.040
there's individual atomic test units.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:42.559
So for these callVals functions, we're

00:07:42.559 --> 00:07:46.399
checking values down an entire column, and there's 13 rows.

00:07:46.399 --> 00:07:49.200
So really, there's 13 individual checks.

00:07:49.200 --> 00:07:52.399
And because we see there's 13 units and 13 pass

00:07:52.399 --> 00:07:55.239
or validation, and we have none that fail,

00:07:55.239 --> 00:07:58.640
we see that all the columns match this expectation

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:04.760
that all values in D are greater than or equal to 0.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:06.559
Great, and we also see other ones,

00:08:06.559 --> 00:08:11.279
which are identity things, like columns are different types.

00:08:11.279 --> 00:08:13.320
They have one test unit because they're checking

00:08:13.320 --> 00:08:15.359
one thing for the type, and we see

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:18.000
that they all seem to pass.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.559
It's only when we get to rows distinct, where

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:23.399
we expect distinct rows across all of our columns,

00:08:23.399 --> 00:08:26.399
basically each row is different from the other,

00:08:26.399 --> 00:08:30.160
we get two failures in this column.

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:34.119
So out of 13 test units, 11 pass, we have two failures.

00:08:34.119 --> 00:08:37.840
That's because we don't have entirely distinct columns

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:42.239
