01:47:56.245 --> 01:48:01.245
But in the Python version, if you want to use AI, you can. There's quite a few avenues for that.

01:48:01.245 --> 01:48:06.245
There's a way to sort of create through LLM's validation plans, which is not dissimilar to draft validation.

01:48:06.245 --> 01:48:11.245
And there's also an assistant in there for just like talking and reasoning through.

01:48:12.245 --> 01:48:17.245
You describe what you want. It knows the API. And you describe which validations you want.

01:48:17.245 --> 01:48:22.245
And it will just like suggest them to you. And you put them in.

01:48:22.245 --> 01:48:27.245
There's also another validation function in that called prompt.

01:48:27.245 --> 01:48:32.245
And what you do there is you just provide text on what the check is.

01:48:32.245 --> 01:48:37.245
So a validation step is essentially a prompt.

01:48:37.245 --> 01:48:42.245
It's a little bit fast. Memorization and such.

01:48:42.245 --> 01:48:47.245
But you're basically using English to validate certain parts of your table with that function.

01:48:47.245 --> 01:48:52.245
Not in the R version yet, but I plan to get those things in due course into the R version.

